<TEXT>
us agriculture secretary richard lyng said 
wednesday he expects congress to pass droughtassistance 
legislation by midaugust but farmers shouldnt expect any help 
until at least october 
i think there will probably be some farmers hanging on the 
edge that may have a terrible time staying in business lyng 
said i hope it will not be a large number 
lyng spoke at a news conference held on one of the farms he 
toured as part of a threeday 10state sweep through areas hard 
hit by the drought of 88 
after stops in iowa and missouri lyng toured farms in north and 
south dakota saying the two states seemed even harder hit than the 
corn belt 
wherever weve gone the effects of the drought are very 
apparent but i must say in the dakotas the problem seems much 
worse lyng said as he toured wheat and barley fields on the farm 
of ed and paul schlosser near spiritwood nd 110 miles east of 
bismarck 
hours later lyng arrived for the night in central minnesota 
inspected a cornfield and said the damage there was the worst he 
has seen in the eight states he had visited 
weve seen other corn that is hurting but i dont think it 
was quite as bad as it is here lyng told edgar traut whose 
family owns and operates a 320acre dairy farm in st cloud 
trauts son dennis 29 said his 170acre corn crop which is only 
waisthigh was of doubtful value even for silage 
you cant come to a farm like this without having some 
emotional impact he said you have to worry about the families 
that are affected 
lyng was scheduled thursday to travel on to wisconisn and 
michigan 
the promise of federal aid did little to encourage one farmer 
theres not much you can do he cant make it rain said joe 
cerveny who farms 160 acres of corn and soybeans south of cedar 
rapids im 72 years old and ive never seen it like this 
lyng looked at a corn crop on kenneth bonttys eastern iowa farm 
and said it was among the hardest hit by the lack of moisture 
its some of the worst corn weve seen in terms of potential 
yield lyng said perhaps the government can come through with 
drought assistance but it doesnt help the corn now 
it is a terrible loss it really is lyng said 
some farmers said teasing rains in the past few weeks had 
skipped the driest parts of iowa 
weve had rain one or two times a week but its just been too 
spotty said stuart towe who farms 550 acres 
lyng toured farms in missouri earlier wednesday and said the 
nations crops will probably suffer severe damage despite recent 
rain 
there is a lot of damage and loss he said in a lot of 
fields there is grave doubt that there will be any harvest 
lyng said it was too early to estimate the dollar loss caused by 
the drought however he said he and a task force will discuss 
their findings after returning to washington dc later this 
week he said he will report monday to president reagan 
lyng continued to resist pleas to allow livestock to graze on 
federal conservation reserve program land despite renewed requests 
from iowa gov terry branstad he also renewed his promise that no 
embargoes on grain would be enforced as a result of the drought 
lyng began his tour tuesday with stops in ohio indiana and 
tennessee 
</TEXT>
