<TEXT>
the governments of angola south africa and cuba 
have approved an agreement in principle for the withdrawal of 
foreign troops from angola and majority rule in namibia according 
to a published report 
the new york times citing unidentified foreign diplomats and 
american officials reported in its wednesday editions that the 
three countries had informed the united states of their acceptance 
of the principles the reagan administration planned to announce 
the development on wednesday the newspaper said 
the statement of principles was initialed by cuban angolan 
and south african negotiators last wednesday at talks held in new 
york and mediated by chester crocker us undersecretary of state 
for african affairs 
the statement called for cuban troops to leave the marxistruled 
southern african nation of angola and for south africa to end its 
73year rule over namibia but did not set a timetable crocker 
said the text of the statement was not made public 
the principles required the approval of the three governments 
after which military and political experts from those nations would 
meet in august to work out details for a settlement 
south africa has said it would accept a un security council 
resolution calling for the independence of southwest africa 
commonly called namibia when the estimated 50000 cuban troops 
withdraw from neighboring angola 
the united states was a party to the talks because it has been 
supporting anticommunist rebels in angola with funds and weapons 
since 1985 angola has been fighting a civil war since it gained 
independence from portugal in 1975 battling anticommunist rebels 
in the south who call themselves unita for national union for the 
total independence of angola 
south africa has repeatedly sent troops from namibia into angola 
to support unita forces in the fighting 
the us goal is a full cuban troop withdrawal in one year the 
same time span that un resolution 435 sets for granting 
independence to namibia angola and cuba had insisted that cuban 
withdrawal take place over four years 
south africa has ruled namibia since world war i under a league 
of nations mandate to administer the territory the leagues 
successor the united nations revoked that mandate 
the four parties began their meetings in london last may 
</TEXT>
