it isnt just in theoretical terms that the 
television networks are forfeiting coverage of the national 
conventions to cable tv at least according to ac nielsen ratings 
for the first night of the democrats 1988 meeting 
ratings for the three major networks coverage has been on a 
slide since 1980 ratings for cable news network though still 
small are up 25 percent in 1988 over 1984 
cspan has also become a player although the extent of its 
audience is not known because it has no advertising and is 
therefore not rated 
for monday nights coverage nbc had a 62 rating and 11 share 
it began at 830 pm edt a halfhour earlier than cbs and abc 
cbs had a 58 and 11 share and abc a 57 and 10 all three major 
networks signed off shortly after 11 pm 
cnn had a 20 rating and a 33 share for its gaveltogavel 
coverage 
for the networks the rating is a percentage of the nations 
estimated 886 million households with television sets and the 
share is a percentage of sets in use for cnn the rating is a 
percentage of households in the cable markets where cnn is 
available roughly half of the total us television homes 
in 1984 the democratic convention had a rating of 84 on cbs 
77 on abc and 71 on nbc the 1980 convention rated a 96 on nbc 
95 on cbs and 80 on abc the rating in 1984 for cnns coverage 
was a 16 
the highest rated democratic convention since the events have 
been televised was the tumultuous 1968 convention in chicago it 
had a rating of 161 on nbc 141 on cbs and 85 on abc 
cspan which is carrying the convention sessions uninterrupted 
by commentary has a potential audience of 38 million households 
and estimates its loyal audience at about 3 million viewers 
