<TEXT>
soviet inspectors today began 
inspecting us nuclear missiles at two british bases greenham 
common and molesworth the us military said 
the 20member soviet team arrived tuesday from moscow for the 
first inspection of bases in britain under the superpower arms 
treaty to dismantle mediumrange nuclear missiles 
soviet team leader vyacheslav s lebedev detailed the inspection 
plan to col john fer of the us onsite inspection agency 
half of the soviets remained at greenham which has 96 missiles 
and five spares and the rest traveled on a threehour bus ride to 
molesworth near cambridge which has 16 missiles 
greenham common is 50 miles west of london molesworth is 50 
miles north of london 
the soviet inspectors spent the night at refurbished 
servicemens quarters at the heart of the greenham common base 
on tuesday night us officers took the team on a bus tour of 
the base it included a visit to a gift shop the black knight 
where they bought small british souvenirs using american currency 
peace protesters who have camped outside the greenham common 
base since before cruise missiles began arriving from the united 
states in november 1983 said they wanted to give a letter to the 
visiting soviets 
the liberal guardian newspaper said the letter read in russian 
we are glad you are making a start on dismantling these terrible 
weapons we hope its the beginning of total disarmament 
lebedev said tuesday that since the inspections began this month 
in the united states the soviet union and west germany no one 
seemed to be cheating 
the experience of the inspections has shown that the ussr 
and united states strictly implemented the treaty signed by them 
and the first steps as to its realization are successful he said 
he spoke through an interpreter from behind a podium emblazoned 
with the emblem of the 16nation north atlantic treaty organization 
the greenham common base commander col richard r riddick 
promised the soviet inspectors help in carrying out your 
specified duties 
the inspections are part of a 60day period of inspections that 
started july 1 to check whether each side told the truth about 
deployments 
the soviets are visiting 30 sites in the united states and five 
western european countries while us inspectors are visiting 133 
soviet sites no violations have been reported 
the intermediate nuclear forces treaty signed in december 
provides for the elimination of all landbased missiles in europe 
with ranges of 300 to 3000 miles 
each side has the right to make 20 shortnotice inspections a 
year at bases until 1991 when all the missiles and their launchers 
should have been destroyed and to make periodic inspections for a 
decade thereafter 
the soviets have the right to enter any buildings they suspect 
could accommodate missiles and additionally can post inspectors at 
base gates to ensure no missiles are removed 
the missiles and their 55foot mobile launchers are housed in 
bunkers the soviets will not see the warheads which do not have 
to be destroyed under the treaty 
the soviets told the americans on monday evening that they were 
coming tuesday under terms of the 16hour notice each side must 
give they are allowed 24 hours for each inspection and can ask for 
eight more hours they must submit a report before they leave 
</TEXT>
