<TEXT>
john w galbreath a former owner of 
baseballs pittsburgh pirates and a breeder of two kentucky derby 
winners died today at 90 
galbreath one of the nations wealthiest men with real estate 
and sports holdings pioneered package deals in which he took 
care of everything for a corporation that wanted a new building 
forbes magazine in 1986 estimated the fortune of galbreath and 
his son dan at 400 million 
galbreath a former chairman of the board of churchill downs in 
lousiville ky got into racing in the 1930s when he bought five 
thoroughbred mares to breed polo ponies 
he said in a 1981 interview that he became convinced the horses 
were too good not to race and once you win youre hooked 
twice his horses won the kentucky derby chateaugay in 1963 and 
proud clarion in 1967 galbreaths horse little current won the 
preakness and the belmont stakes in 1974 
galbreath along with three partners including singer bing 
crosby purchased the pirates in 1946 galbreath was named 
president of the team in 1950 in 1969 he was succeeded by his son 
dan 
the galbreaths sold their interests in the club in 1985 
under galbreaths ownership the pirates won the world series in 
1960 on bill mazeroskis dramatic seventhgame ninthinning home 
run in 1971 and again in 1979 
in the 1970s the pirates also won six division championships 
and two national league pennants 
galbreath was born in derby south of columbus and graduated 
from ohio university 
galbreath began his business career in 1920 joining a 
fraternity brother in the real estate business he began his own 
business a few years later 
although he said he suffered losses during the stock market 
crash of 1929 galbreath began buying properties at low prices 
during the 1930s consolidating them and selling them in package 
form to those in search of investments 
major projects included the town of kearny ariz to serve a 
mining installation by kennecott copper corp and a 2000home 
project in fairless hills pa to serve the fairless works of the 
former us steel corp 
he acquired such buildings as the soconymobil building in new 
york city a 39story office building in pittsburgh whose private 
tenant was mellon bank and the 40story union bank square in los 
angeles 
galbreath was twice widowed survivors in addition to his son 
include a daughter and seven grandchildren 
a memorial service was set for saturday in marble cliff with 
the rev norman vincent peale officiating 
</TEXT>
