tough prison sentences for hardened criminals serve the cause of 
justice but some fear that they cost more than taxpayers can 
afford 
a recent justice department study has some reassuring news 
keeping repeat offenders behind bars actually is cheaper than 
granting them early release 
the departments research arm the national institute of 
justice found that the average prisoner costs 25000 a year 
including prison construction and maintenance expenses 
but crimes committed by repeat offenders who have been freed 
early cost about 430000 a year in losses to victims and in 
outlays for police courts etc 
it is true that many prisons are overcrowded the remedy is not 
to turn their inmates loose but to build more prisons 
