<TEXT>
the hoover institution the thinktank 
that generated many of the reagan administrations conservative 
ideas must pick a new leader of its own following a decision by 
its longtime director to step down 
w glenn campbells decision follows months of debate about the 
affiliation between stanford university and the oncampus 
institution that will soon be home to secretary of state george 
shultz and attorney general edwin meese iii 
campbell who succeeded founder and former president herbert 
hoover in 1960 said the new director will have to be a leader 
who can provide a climate where all these prima donnas can live 
together 
the announcement came two months after campbell vowed to sue if 
stanford tried to oust him at 65 because it was the customary 
retirement age at the university campbell had planned on staying 
another five years 
campbell said he is stepping aside in part because hes weary of 
fighting stanford i used to be a young warrior now im an aging 
warrior but not yet an old warrior he said 
six nobel laureates are associated with the think tank 
including economist milton friedman and soviet writer alexander 
solzhenitsyn 
president reagan is an honorary fellow and several of his 
advisers including economist martin anderson national security 
expert richard allen and special envoy philip habib are among the 
more than 100 hoover scholars 
campbell met with hoovers board of overseers on wednesday and 
said he would make a public statement thursday at the conclusion of 
the meeting 
however in an interview monday with the associated press he 
described his decision his vision of hoovers future and his 
assessment of its achievements under his leadership 
his legacy he said is the development of an institution of 
ideas and distinction filled with distinguished scholars who can 
exchange ideas with each other 
he is proud that hoover participated in the reagan 
revolution and in the promotion of peace he said 
over the next decade he said hed like to see hoover 
strengthen its pacific basin program create a fund for the 
promotion of peace reach out more to the public through the media 
and become the site of a separate professional school for 
international relations 
campbell said hoover will keep its independence from stanford 
and remain an important policy research center 
i hope the president will come here regularly again after he 
gets over his annoyance with stanfords administration and 
faculty campbell said referring to the universitys rejection 
last year of a reagan library and policy center 
meese has accepted campbells invitation to join hoover as a 
visiting fellow while he writes a book on his years with reagan 
shultz an honorary fellow will return to work on a series of 
documentaries on policymaking at the state department while he 
teaches a public policy course at stanfords graduate school of 
business 
campbell said he would not fight the decision of stanfords 
trustees to retire him next year probably about six months after 
he turns 65 in april but said he wanted to make sure there is a 
smooth transition to his successor 
he said he would hold the title of counselor serve as 
exofficio member of all selection and advisory committees and 
stay in his current office formerly occupied by president hoover 
campbell had originally called stanfords effort to retire him 
an attempted takeover motivated by politics and greed and noted 
several exceptions to the retireat65 rule 
stanford president donald kennedy and former trustees president 
warren christopher were carter administration officials and the 
majority of the faculty are democrats 
campbell an unabashed conservative republican said the problem 
between hoover and stanford is not as simple as politics alone 
all these people at stanford want is the money and 
buildings said campbell whose large woodpaneled office is on 
the 11th floor of the landmark hoover tower in the center of campus 
campbell a harvard economist who once had former federal 
reserve board chairman paul volcker as a student helped boost a 2 
million endowment to its current level of more than 110 million 
john f manley a liberal professor of political science at 
stanford and a longtime hoover institution critic has denounced it 
as a political operation in the midst of what is supposed to be a 
nonpartisan university 
however seymour martin lipset a hoover sociologist and 
political scientist and former johnson administration official 
said hoover should not be labeled a conservative think tank 
he said hoovers fellows have a range of political opinions 
and interests that covers the gamut from socialist to extreme 
conservative 
