<DOCNO> AP880720-0185 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the environmental protection agency on 
wednesday delayed developing regulations for more controls on the 
leukemiacausing air pollutant benzene until it hears from the 
public on what is an acceptable environmental risk 
the approach the agency adopts for benzene one of the most 
widely used of all chemicals is expected to set the standard for 
agency rulings on acceptable levels of risk for dozens of other air 
pollutants 
one question is should we opt for additional controls that 
may be expensive but only buy society little additional 
reduction epa administrator lee m thomas said in a statement 
announcing the delay 
currently about 10 cases of leukemia occur in the general 
population every three years as a result of leaks from plant 
equipment and other exposure from making and using benzene the 
chemical is used in making gasoline plastics rubber artificial 
fibers and many other chemicals 
under the plans the epa is considering about one death every 
other year would result from benzene exposure 
environmentalists have sought standards that in effect would 
result in one death every 550 years the epa believes that such 
stringent standards would force massive plant closings and lead to 
the loss of thousands of jobs 
at issue in the matter is whether environmental risk should 
depend on where a person lives some analysts contend that society 
has already answered that question by refusing to allow such 
facilities as nuclear power plants to be built in urban areas but 
allowing them in the countryside 
with benzene the epa is trying to decide whether to rule that 
nobody living near industrial sources should face a lifetime risk 
greater than one in a million as the environmentalists argue or 
whether larger risks to individuals should be allowed when few 
people are exposed and the expected number of cancers is small 
the agency asked for maximum public comment on the 
sidetracked plan and three others in order of increasing 
stringency those others would 
limit annual cases of leukemia to one in the entire population 
this would mean little cost to industry 
limit the maximum likely risk to the most exposed individual to 
one in 10000 ignoring total cases 
limit the maximum likely risk to one in a million this the 
epa said could result in the closing of 131 chemical plants that 
couldnt control leaks and the loss of 35000 jobs plus the 
closing of 44 cokeoven byproduct recovery plants and the loss of 
7000 jobs 
david doniger an attorney for the natural resources defense 
council said that he was gratified that the oneinamillion 
risk standard is under serious consideration and was almost 
certain that epa had greatly overestimated the costs of compliance 
he said it appeared the agency had not considered the ability of 
industry to pass on cost increases in prices and also that epa 
assumed all plants would have to reduce emissions by the same 
proportion as the dirtiest plants 
he said the epa also ignored the possibility that industry could 
develop new technologies to control benzene emissions 
the epas current benzene regulations which were adopted in 
1984 were challenged in court by doniger the agency had a court 
deadline to make a proposal by wednesday and a decision by december 
the us circuit court of appeals for the district of columbia 
said last year in a decision on another pollutant vinyl chloride 
that the epa must disregard all questions of costs in deciding 
acceptable risks but may consider costs and feasibility in 
deciding the ample margin of safety called for by the law 
the american petroleum institute said in a statement that the 
new proposal offered a good opportunity to develop a workable 
program in this area and that it hoped the epa would resist 
the unreasonable demands of environmental groups to adopt 
standards that are almost zerorisk 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

