<TEXT>
the united states will mediate fourway talks 
in switzerland starting aug 2 aimed at working out a final 
agreement on the withdrawal of foreign forces from angola and on 
namibian independence from south africa it was announced wedneday 
assistant secretary of state chester crocker made the 
announcement after south africa cuba and angola the other 
participants in the talks gave final endorsement to a statement 
of principles governing future negotiations 
this is an important step we are not saying it is more than 
that crocker told a news conference there are a great many 
hard and difficult compromises to be achieved 
the statement of principles was worked out on a tentative basis 
last week during talks in new york but it left unresolved the 
thorny question of the timetables during which the withdrawals 
would take place this has emerged as the major area of 
disagreement among the parties 
aside from the timetable issue crocker said the statement of 
principles clears the way for the drafting of treaties discussions 
on verification of a final agreement and a process for the 
disengagement of forces 
the united states has been serving as mediator for the fourway 
talks which began in early may the previous rounds were held in 
london cairo and new york the switzerland talks will take place 
in geneva 
the administrations involvement in the issue dates back to 1981 
when crocker began pursuing a settlement that would lead to the 
withdrawal of cuban and south african forces from angola and south 
african consent to independence for namibia africas last colony 
