<TEXT>
soviet inspectors counted us 
nuclear missiles in britain wednesday under the historic superpower 
treaty to eliminate an entire class of such weapons but they want 
to see the tower of london too 
at the beginning of the inspection they requested a 
sightseeing visit to london defense ministry spokesman martin 
helm said wednesday 
clearly theres no provision in the inf intermediaterange 
nuclear forces treaty for the inspectors and air crew to move off 
base but we will be pleased to arrange a trip to make the visit 
enjoyable he added 
so thursday will be sightseeing day for the 20 soviet 
inspectors 
the inspectors flew in tuesday from moscow to make their checks 
at greenham common airbase 50 miles west of london and at 
britains other cruise missile base molesworth near cambridge 
both bases are run by the us military 
the checks are part of a 60day period of inspections that 
started july 1 to verify whether each side told the truth about 
deployments the soviets are visiting 30 sites in the united states 
and five western european countries us inspectors are visiting 
133 sites in the soviet union and eastern europe no violations 
have been reported thus far 
a group of 20 us missile experts on wednesday ended their 
inspections of installations in east germany the official east 
german news agency adn said 
it said the americans split into two groups to inspect four 
former soviet missile sites in waren bischofswerda wokul and 
koenigsbrueck east germany 
also wednesday the official czechoslovak news agency ctk said 
the government granted permission for us experts to inspect a 
former missile base at hranice central czechoslovakia under the 
inf treaty it said the 10 americans will arrive thursday 
the inf treaty signed in december provides for elimination 
within three years of all landbased missiles in europe with ranges 
of 300 to 3000 miles the soviet inspectors began their checks in 
britain at noon wednesday splitting up into two teams to visit 
both bases 
under the ussoviet treaty which provided for unprecedented 
review of each others facilities each inspection can last up to 
24 hours with a possible eighthour extension 
the soviets who gave the required 16 hours notice of arrival 
and declared formally wednesday morning what they wanted to see 
may take four hours to write their reports after inspections 
the inspections at greenham common with 96 working missiles 
and molesworth with 16 are the first in britain 
the groundhugging difficulttodetect cruise missiles which 
provide a vehicle for the warheads and their 55foot mobile 
launchers are housed in bunkers the soviets will not see the 
warheads which carry the explosive material because the warheads 
do not have to be destroyed under the treaty 
the soviet inspectors were staying in specially converted 
barracks 
entertainment to date consisted of a bus tour of the greenham 
base tuesday evening and a visit to an onbase gift shop the us 
military said 
but on thursday after being cooped up under tight security with 
geiger counters tape measures missiles and mobile launchers the 
