<TEXT>
a fleet of little wooden 
dhows dart daily past the supertankers and warships of the persian 
gulf carrying on a historic link between wartorn iran and arab 
dubai 
we bring lots of onions from iran watermelons any kind of 
food and fruits that we can said hossein a crewman who aboard a 
dhow docked at dubais busy waterfront 
stacked and strewn all along the dock were piles of tires boxed 
washing machines and automobile parts bicycles and bedsprings 
consumer goods destined for iran aboard dhows 
the handmade dhows have sailed the 150 miles from dubai to 
bandar abbas in iran for generations but with the iraniraq war 
the route has taken on added importance 
most of the other gulf countries except for dubai and kuwait 
have cut their trade links with iran so most of the stuff we 
bring here goes to the other gulf countries its sort of a 
collection point for us said capt avaz oveisi who has spent 34 
of his 62 years sailing dhows 
iranians by the thousands those who can find foreign currency 
fly into dubai to shop and send the goods back home by dhow 
if the goods are new the pattern isnt dubais ports and 
merchants once dealt in pearls and silk 
dubai is a trading place they were smuggling and trading with 
the rest of the world for centuries said daniel greenwald 
executive vice president of the american business council of dubai 
even in the days of container shipping greenwald said it can be 
very economical to use the little dhows which can tie up in 
small ports and unload their cargoes quickly 
the boats generally take eight to 12 hours to cross the gulf an 
arduous journey where temperatures can climb to 110 degrees or 
more with humidity at 90 percent 
its really tiring to work on a dhow all the day in all of the 
heat and to load and unload said abbas abassi a dhow 
crewman 
despite the dozens of warships cruising the gulf none of the 
dhow crewmen said they had been threatened although some said they 
were worried after a us ship shot down an iran air jetliner 
since the airplane has been hit were very scared but there 
hasnt been any real incident abassi said 
even if theyre scared they have to do it because this is the 
way they make money for their families 
